gin": 632, "end": 638}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7536249160766602, "span": {"begin": 667, "end": 670}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9866242408752441, "span": {"begin": 714, "end": 719}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8929515480995178, "span": {"begin": 720, "end": 725}}], "text": "The KER as such is biologically plausible and strong.&nbsp;DNA strand breaks, if not resulting in cell death, may lead to chromosomal translocation in the surviving cell population (McClendon et al. 2007).&nbsp; DNA breaks and MLL rearrangements by etoposide and bioflavonoids have been demonstrated in human fetal liver haematopoietic stem cells, in human embryonic stem cells and in human prehaematopoietic mesenchymal stem cells as well as in cord blood mononuclear cells (Ishii et al 2002; Blanco et al 2004; Moneypenny et al 2006; Bueno et al 2009; Menendez et al 2009), which&nbsp;shows that DSB (in this specific case due to TopoII poisoning) -associated&nbsp;MLL rearrangements are produced in appropriate human cells in utero.  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:00:03 +0000 2026"}